  <body>
    <Header/>

    <div class="profile-text">

      <p>I'm a third-year Applied Mathematics student at UNH, concentrating in Computation and Algorithm Analysis, and a member of the Hamel Honors and Scholars 
        College. My technical interests span cryptography, machine learning, and operating systems, and technical expreience includes Rust, Python, C/C++, and 
        CI/CD infrastructure management. Currently, I work at InterOperability Labs as a DevOps engineer on the DPDK project, supporting open-source network
        infrastructure initiatives, and at AI Foundry as a software engineer doing inference engineering. When I'm not studying or at the gym, I'm experimenting
        with coffee, playing guitar, writing poetry, or exploring the outdoors.</p>
    <p>Contact: <span id="copy-email" class="clickable-email">mail [at] mlabrecque (dot) dev</span></p>

    </div>

    <hr class="solid">

    <h2>Projects</h2>
      <div class="project-grid">
      
        <Project
          title="Billboard Top-40 Tracker"
        description="A Python-based utility designed to automate the retrieval the performance data of music which appeared on the Billboard Top 100. The tool 
        allows users to query current and past Top 100 rankings, and returns the number of songs a given artist has in the Top 100, as well as the name of any
        song which placed in the Top 40. The reason I created this utility was to assist myself and other DJ’s at WUNH, the college radio station at UNH, which
        has a strict “no Top 40” policy for playing music. This project focuses on clean data extraction, error handling, and modular script design, providing a
        lightweight yet robust way to monitor trends in the music industry. "
        tags={["Python", "Data Processing", "Data Analytics"]}
        />
      
        <Project
          title="Fedora Giulia Spin"
          description="A specialized Linux workstation for developers built on the Fedora “leading-edge” philosophy with the goal of offering a high-performance, 
          out-of-the-box experience for developers who want 90% of the efficiency of a custom TWM without the configuration overhead. It features a preconfigured workflow 
          centered around the Niri scrolling window manager. Giulia is designed as a general-purpose developer suite, providing batteries-included support
          for Rust, Go, Python, Java, and C/C++, alongside a container-ready Podman environment and a LazyVim-powered Neovim setup."
        tags={["Linux", "System Automation", "Podman"]}
        />

        <Project
          title = "Playcaller"
        description="Playcaller is an infrastructure automation tool built around the concept of Disposable Development Environments — environments 
        that can be torn down and reproduced with minimal downtime. Using Ansible as a declarative backend, Playcaller codifies the entire development environment into
        version-controlled playbooks, enabling reproducible machine setup across any UNIX-based system. A core component is a PostgreSQL database that serves as a 
        cross-distro package registry, ensuring that when Playcaller assembles an Ansible pipeline,
        it resolves the correct package name for the target system regardless of distribution. This eliminates a major pain point in multi-platform automation and
        reflects a deliberate focus on correctness and portability over quick scripting."
          tags={["Ansible", "Python", "PostgreSQL", "IaC", "Configuration Management"]}
        />

      <!--<Project
